caption: Fresh seafood at unbelievable prices. King and snow crab feast for $42 was so good!

I have been to this place about 25 times, always getting the same things - Oysters, Crab Cakes, King Crab dinner. My trip last weekend will be my last. They use to sell the King Crab dinner for $35 and it was by far the best you could get in Chicago. At this price and considering how much food you got, there was just no comparison to other restaurants. Unfortunately, the price had gone up incrementally over the last two years and is now about $50. I realize crab is market based, but I’m aware of current costs and quality. At this price, I think there are some better competitors in the area (Crab House, Crab Cellar, etc). It’s a somewhat run down basement bar and it’s not very clean to be honest. I can’t really justify the price for the quality of restaurant. I think most locals would “just deal with it” when the cost was $35 for the dinner. It’s also cash only, so you know they are not paying transaction fees and... taxes. Hats off too which is another pet peeve of theirs customers put up with, a valid request for a higher end restaurant but hardly appropriate for a dungy basement bar. Still a good place, but just not what it use to be. Too bad.

"This place has not changed in years, not one bit!" My mother stated this as we are walking in the front door of Half Shell from a day at the beach. Taking a step into the past; you walk into an old 1970s bar, with a fire place in the corner, low ceilings, and dim lighting, you feel right at home and in your comfort zone. The beers are ice cold just the way we all like it. Now, one thing about the seafood here, the food is down-right fantastic. Oysters, shrimp, king and snow crab legs, frog legs, scallops, you name it. And what's even better, the price! The price is just right to get a bang for your bucks. But beware, the bar has yet to change in forty years and that means no modern day payment methods, this place is cash only! However, the freshness of the food, the experience of past life and ice cold beers could have in there for a few hours. Give half shell a try, you will not be disappointed and I can guarantee that!

It was between this dive and Low Country.  We should have gone to Low Country!!!  It started off with not being able to sit because all of are party had not arrived (they were looking for a parking spot).  So we sat at the bar by 17 year old included. I was there with my parents 77 & 73 years old  for my mothers birthday (she was equipped with a portable oxygen machine).  A waitress came into the restaurant in the basement and said the table for 5 is ready (she was speaking to the bartender) he then says you can go out.....we had to find the table.  Waitress Carmen come over to take out order and we informed her there would be 3 checks shes says " I can't do that you will have to figure that out yourself" It was down hill after that.  We picked Half Shell because of the size of the crab legs and the Chubbs.  Well guess what? They have on the menus but do not sell it.  My father had a hamburger instead   They king crab legs were Ok but they didn't provide enough utensil, even red lobster does that.  Our waitress Carmen was not attentive at all my daughter had to get condiments for the hamburger because Carmen never came back to ask what we needed.  The other servers attended us.  Our bill was $154.00 we would have given a nice tip but Carmen attended to everyone but us maybe she thought because we wanted separate checks our order was going to be light. Maybe its because we were black (saw her treat an African american couple with a small child not so nicely as well, seated a white couple first even though the black couple was there first) What ever the case I will never go back to half shell, the food was okay, I don't see what the hype was all about and Carmen is the worst!

This local restaurant manages to consistently serve the very best crab in the city while flying under the radar. It's been here forever and for a good reason.  It's definitely a no-frills place, so if you're looking for fancy or formal, this basement hideaway is not for you.  But if you want good service and the best King crab legs you'll ever have, head over to Half Shell. We couldn't finish ours.  Nothing exceptional for wines, but again, you're going for the seafood and the cozy, friendly ambience.  Fried shrimp and oysters literally go poof in your mouth. Not a fan of the smelt, but they're dressed and if you like smelt I imagine they're quite tasty.  It's the perfect spot on a cold snowy night - they have a small fireplace that warms the entire space.  NOTE: they are CASH ONLY.
